IRS990.MissionDesc: Guided by God's love, our mission is to provide compassionate service to all people in need throughout northern Kansas. We do this in a variety of ways which include (a) financial and housing assistance, (b) personal care and basic needs such as food hygiene, diapers and clothing, (c) counseling services, (d) immigration legal services, (e) pregnancy support and adoption services, and (f) a thrift store in Salina, Kansas.
IRS990.Desc: The Organization provides direct financial support for the purchase of (1) basic goods (clothing, food, household items, etc.), (2) rent and utility costs, (3) prescriptions and medical supplies, (4) predatory debt relief, and (5) disaster relief.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: Adoption programs work with birth parents and adoptive couples to facilitate infant adoption services, conduct home studies, and assist with search and reunion services. In working with birth parents, the Organization helps explore thoughts and feelings about parenting as well as create an adoption plan. A final decision about any adoption belongs to the birth parents. Adoptions are open as the Organization believes children are best served by preserving their connection to their family of origin. In addition, the Organization provides a pregnancy support program focused on helping deliver health, full-term babies using as individualized plan designed for each mother that may include counseling and support, pregnancy and infant items, limited financial assistance and help locating resources.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: The Organizations immigration legal services provide a quality service to people of all faiths and nationalities. Started by the Sisters of St. Joseph in 1995 the Organization has assisted thousands of people to gain Lawful Permanent Residence status and obtain United States Citizenship. The statistics of the Organizations services reflect positive outcomes in helping numerous people achieve a better lifestyle in the United States of America. The Organization specializes in providing benefit eligibility determination for citizenship work authorizations and other related services including Family immigration applications and Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals. If the Organizations immigration attorney is unable to assist with a particular immigration need an appropriate referral is made.

ProgSrvcAccomActyOtherGrp.Desc: Mental health counseling and therapy services are provided for children and adolescents, adults, family, marriage and couples and divorce adjustment. These services are provided regardless of religion, race, nationality, age or financial status.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The endowment was established to support catastrophic illness, youth assistance and general operating purposes.

The Organization is organized as a Kansas nonprofit corporation and has been recognized by the IRS as exempt from federal income taxes under IRC Section 501(a) as an organization described in IRC Section 501(c)(3). Further, the Organization qualifies for the charitable contribution deduction under IRC Sections 170(b)(1)(A)(vi) and has been determined not to be a private foundation under IRC Sections 509(a)(1). The Organization is annually required to file a Return of Organization Exempt from Income Tax (Form 990) with the IRS. In addition, the Organization is subject to income tax on net income that is derived from business activities that are unrelated to its exempt purposes. For the years ended June 30, 2023 and 2022, the Organization has determined that it is not subject to unrelated business income tax and has not filed an Exempt Organization Business Income Tax Return (Form 990-T) with the IRS. Returns filed by the Organization are subject to IRS examination, generally for three years after each return is filed. No taxing authorities have commenced income tax examinations for open tax years.
